INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7d7a5697-5199-479c-bca9-69090b2e8926',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL's REST Blind Spots — Status Codes, Idempotency, and the Single Endpoint$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL abandons REST's per-resource URL structure for a single POST /graphql endpoint, quietly breaking several HTTP conventions. The most dangerous: status codes. A GraphQL response is almost always 200 OK — even when a resolver throws. Errors live in the response body's `errors` array, not the status code. Any middleware or monitoring that gates on non-2xx will silently pass through application-level failures.

Idempotency shifts too. GraphQL queries are naturally idempotent — same query + same variables = same result, safe to retry. Mutations are not, unless explicitly designed as such (e.g., upserts keyed on a stable `id`). There's no HTTP verb to signal this distinction; the `query` vs `mutation` keyword is your only contract, and clients must respect it.

One place REST semantics resurface meaningfully: persisted queries. Apollo's Automatic Persisted Queries (APQ) and Relay's `@persistQueryString` allow read operations to be sent via HTTP GET, restoring CDN cacheability for query-heavy traffic. Without this, every GraphQL read is a POST — uncacheable by default at the network layer.$escape$,
  $escape$// ❌ REST-style: status code won't catch GraphQL errors
const res = await fetch('/graphql', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ query: GET_USER }),
});
if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed'); // 200 even on resolver errors

// ✅ Always inspect the errors array
const { data, errors } = await res.json();
if (errors?.length) throw new Error(errors[0].message);

// ✅ Persisted query via GET — CDN-cacheable
const params = new URLSearchParams({
  extensions: JSON.stringify({ persistedQuery: { version: 1, sha256Hash: queryHash } }),
});
const cached = await fetch(`/graphql?${params}`); // GET is safe for queries$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
