INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cd207bce-6489-4732-9d00-46dd2bc9b9ec',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL vs gRPC — Protobuf Schemas, Streaming Types, and When to Drop REST Entirely$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL's SDL and gRPC's `.proto` files solve the same core problem — contract-first, typed interfaces — but gRPC operates below the HTTP application layer using binary Protocol Buffer serialization instead of JSON. Where GraphQL gives clients a single flexible endpoint, gRPC defines strongly-typed RPC methods with generated client stubs.

gRPC supports four streaming patterns that map directly to concepts GraphQL developers know: unary (identical to a query/mutation round-trip), server streaming (like a subscription, but over HTTP/2 multiplexing instead of WebSockets), client streaming, and bidirectional streaming. gRPC streams carry significantly lower overhead because there's no subscription resolver, no WebSocket handshake, and no JSON parse cost.

The practical split: keep GraphQL at the BFF/gateway layer where flexible client queries matter. Push gRPC into internal service-to-service communication — embedding pipelines, ranking services, or any call hitting 5k+ RPS where JSON serialization overhead compounds. In most GraphQL architectures, resolvers end up calling gRPC backends anyway. Modeling that boundary explicitly avoids the anti-pattern of REST hops between internal services that already share a schema contract.$escape$,
  $escape$// Proto mirrors your GraphQL SDL — contract-first, strongly typed
// type Query { getUser(id: ID!): User }
// type Subscription { userFeed(filter: String!): User }

service UserService {
  rpc GetUser(UserRequest) returns (UserResponse);              // unary = query
  rpc StreamUserFeed(FeedFilter) returns (stream UserResponse); // server stream = subscription
}

// GraphQL resolver delegating to gRPC backend
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    user: (_, { id }, { grpcClient }) =>
      promisify(grpcClient.getUser.bind(grpcClient))({ id }),
  },
};$escape$,
