INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '85d2bcf7-2d79-4f5d-a198-446aa0f09ca2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL Filtering & Sorting — Designing Args That Scale$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL has no built-in filtering or sorting conventions, so the community has converged on structured input types rather than ad-hoc scalar arguments. The Relay spec popularized `first`/`after` for pagination, but for filtering and sorting you should define dedicated input types: a `FilterInput` for predicates and an `OrderByInput` for sort fields plus direction.

Avoid flat args like `nameContains: String, sortBy: String, sortDir: String`. They don't compose and break as fields grow. Instead, define `filter: UserFilterInput` and `orderBy: [UserOrderByInput!]`. Using a list for `orderBy` naturally supports multi-column sorting.

On the resolver side, map these input types to your ORM or SQL builder — never interpolate them directly into raw queries. Validate enum values at the GraphQL schema layer using `enum SortDirection { ASC DESC }` so invalid inputs are rejected before they hit your data layer.

This pattern keeps your schema self-documenting: introspection reveals exactly which fields are filterable and sortable without external API docs.$escape$,
  $escape$enum SortDirection { ASC DESC }

enum UserSortField { NAME EMAIL CREATED_AT }

input UserFilterInput {
  nameContains: String
  isActive: Boolean
  createdAfter: DateTime
}

input UserOrderByInput {
  field: UserSortField!
  direction: SortDirection!
}

type Query {
  users(
    filter: UserFilterInput
    orderBy: [UserOrderByInput!]
    first: Int
    after: String
  ): UserConnection!
}$escape$,
  $escape$graphql$escape$,
