INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3098d696-6c0c-4b9b-b600-ace03d0ba02f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL Pagination — Cursor vs Offset, Total Counts, and Infinite Scroll$escape$,
  $escape$Offset pagination (`first: 10, offset: 20`) is simple but breaks under concurrent writes — a new row inserted mid-scroll shifts every subsequent page. Cursor-based pagination solves this. The Relay Connection spec is the de facto standard: `edges[].cursor` is an opaque, base64-encoded pointer (usually a row ID or timestamp), and `pageInfo` exposes `hasNextPage` / `endCursor`. Pass `after: $endCursor` on the next fetch to resume exactly where you left off.

For infinite scroll, store `endCursor` in component state and merge incoming `edges` into the existing list. Apollo Client's `fetchMore` handles this cleanly — use a `merge` field policy on the type to concatenate edge arrays rather than replace them.

Avoid `totalCount` unless the UI explicitly needs it. It forces a `COUNT(*)` subquery on every request, which is expensive on large tables. If you need it, request it only on the first page fetch via a separate field or a `@skip(if: $skipCount)` directive. Never include it in subsequent `fetchMore` calls.$escape$,
  $escape$const { data, fetchMore } = useQuery(FEED_QUERY, {
  variables: { first: 20 },
});

// Apollo field policy — merge edges instead of replacing
const cache = new InMemoryCache({
  typePolicies: {
    Query: {
      fields: {
        feed: relayStylePagination(), // handles cursor merging automatically
      },
    },
  },
});

// Load next page
fetchMore({
  variables: { after: data.feed.pageInfo.endCursor },
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
