INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1b8f1791-8007-4c2a-aa76-9527138bdd59',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL Idempotency Keys — Making Mutations Safe to Retry$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL queries are both safe (no side effects) and idempotent — repeating them never changes server state. Mutations are neither. A retried `createOrder` mutation can create duplicate orders, charge customers twice, or corrupt state if the network hiccups mid-flight.

The fix: add an `idempotencyKey: ID!` argument to sensitive mutations. The resolver checks a cache (Redis or a DB table) — if the key already exists, it returns the stored result instead of re-executing. Keys are client-generated UUIDs tied to the logical operation, not the request.

Apollo Server has no built-in idempotency middleware, so you implement this in the resolver or a shared util. Store `(key, result, expiresAt)` — a 24-hour TTL is typical for payment flows. The response shape must be identical on replay, so cache the full resolver return value, not just a status flag.

Critically, `idempotencyKey` should be defined on the mutation input type, not as a standalone argument, so it travels cleanly through fragments and generated client types.$escape$,
  $escape$// Mutation definition
type Mutation {
  createOrder(input: CreateOrderInput!): OrderPayload!
}

input CreateOrderInput {
  idempotencyKey: ID!
  items: [OrderItemInput!]!
}

// Resolver (Apollo Server)
async createOrder(_: unknown, { input }: Args, { redis }: Context) {
  const cached = await redis.get(`idem:${input.idempotencyKey}`);
  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached);

  const order = await db.orders.create(input);
  await redis.setex(`idem:${input.idempotencyKey}`, 86400, JSON.stringify(order));
  return order;
}$escape$,
