INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1309890b-f497-4b60-b849-7fcc80f80ba4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL's Place in the REST vs GraphQL vs gRPC Decision Framework$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL wins when clients have divergent data needs. A mobile client fetching a lean `{ user { id name } }` and a dashboard running a complex nested query with fragments both hit the same endpoint — no versioning, no over-fetching. The schema acts as a contract: `type Query { user(id: ID!): User }` is self-documenting and introspectable via `__schema`. Where GraphQL loses: binary streaming (gRPC wins with Protobuf), simple CRUD with uniform payloads (REST is lighter), and N+1 query traps without DataLoader batching. Choose GraphQL when: (1) multiple clients consume the same API with different shape requirements, (2) rapid frontend iteration is a priority and BFF round-trips are costly, (3) you need real-time via `Subscription` types alongside queries. Avoid it for file uploads, highly cacheable public APIs (HTTP cache headers don't map cleanly to POST-based GraphQL), or teams unfamiliar with resolver depth and schema design costs. The schema-first workflow with tools like `graphql-codegen` generating typed hooks is the real forcing function — it makes GraphQL's overhead pay off at scale.$escape$,
  $escape$# Introspect your schema to validate the contract before switching protocols
curl -X POST https://api.example.com/graphql \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{
    "query": "{ __schema { types { name kind fields { name type { name } } } } }"
  }' | jq '.data.__schema.types[] | select(.name == "User")'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
