INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '908ecfe1-7c86-4518-a468-5566e78055bb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GraphQL Performance — Shrinking Payloads, Reusing Connections, and Multiplexing Subscriptions$escape$,
  $escape$GraphQL's flexible selection sets can still balloon payloads when clients over-fetch or send large query strings repeatedly. Three levers address this directly.

Automatic Persisted Queries (APQ): Apollo Client hashes the query with SHA-256 and sends only the hash. On a cache miss, the server requests the full document once; every subsequent request transmits the hash alone — cutting wire size 70–90% for deeply nested queries.

Brotli compression: GraphQL responses are JSON — highly repetitive and compressible. Set `Accept-Encoding: br` on the client and enable Brotli on Apollo Server via `expressMiddleware` with a compression middleware. Brotli achieves 15–25% better ratios than gzip on typical JSON payloads.

Subscription transport and HTTP/2 multiplexing: WebSocket-based subscriptions (`graphql-ws`) open a dedicated TCP connection per client. Migrating to `graphql-sse` (Server-Sent Events) lets subscriptions ride existing HTTP/2 streams, enabling true multiplexing and eliminating per-subscription handshake overhead. Pair this with `keepalive: true` on your `HttpLink` fetch options to reuse connections across query/mutation traffic.$escape$,
  $escape$import { ApolloClient, InMemoryCache, HttpLink } from '@apollo/client';
import { createPersistedQueryLink } from '@apollo/client/link/persisted-queries';
import { sha256 } from 'crypto-hash';

const apqLink = createPersistedQueryLink({ sha256 });

const httpLink = new HttpLink({
  uri: '/graphql',
  headers: { 'Accept-Encoding': 'br, gzip' },
  fetchOptions: { keepalive: true },
});

export const client = new ApolloClient({
  cache: new InMemoryCache(),
  link: apqLink.concat(httpLink),
});$escape$,
